    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense. so if i use a generator to stream the data, i won't hit that memory error anymore, right? i'm also worried about actual memory leaks though. like, if i'm constantly creating these new objects while processing, how do i know if something is actually \"leaking\" and eating up my resources in the background?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You're on the right track, but remember that even with generators, you still need to be careful about what you *do* with the data once you pull it out. A generator prevents the initial massive load, but if you're building up huge intermediate structures inside your loop, you can still cause trouble.\n\nA memory leak, in this context, is usually when an object that you no longer need is still being referenced somewhere, keeping it alive in memory. To spot this, you need tools! You can use Python's built-in `gc` module to monitor garbage collection, or more powerfully, external profilers like `memory_profiler`. These tools let you watch exactly where memory is being allocated and, more importantly, where it's *not* being released.",
      "source": "target",
